Small boats in 713

Ernesto

June 4, 2018

Targets

Total landed biomass

Let’s start by collecting all boats whose primary WPP is either 712 or 713 and arrange them by size type.

Type of Boat GT Range Count
Nano <5GT 90
Small 5-14 GT 158
Medium 15-29 GT 108
Big 30+ GT 53
NA Unknown 178

Let’s assume for a second the same gear throughout and all uknowns are small boats. I take the average GT landed per boat class from Jos’ CpUE report and compute the expected landed in tonnes for each boat class.

Class Summed GT Tally Average GT Landed Expected Landings (T)
Nano 335 90 3.3 298
Small 1273 158 13.2 2085
Medium 2680 108 15.8 1709
Big 2884 53 35.3 1872

This mean that a model for small boats in 712-713 will be “realistic” if it lands approximately 2,085 tonnes per year.

Small Boats

Proportion

Focus only on the small boats in 712-713 and their landings. It turns out that they are predominantly catching malabaricus (50% of the catch) and everything else is of minor importance (even multidens).

If we focus on the 5 species we isolated from cluster analysis:

We would like the proportion in our model to be similar.

Simulation outputs

We can coherce the model to behave (in particular the 3 important ones are: landings of about 2000T, little multidens caught, much malabaricus caught). I am not very confident about duration and distance because I don’t have Ren’s data yet, so I am using a single observation from Josep’s table. The profits target of 50M IDR a trip comes from the surveys. It’s a bit too low because we are only modelling gas as operating costs (in our model a boat spends about 600,000 IDR a day out, but surveys suggest 1M a day)

Medium

There are 108 of them. They are mostly catching multidens, in proportion:

Species Weight Caught (kg) Weight Caught (%) Fish Value (IDR) Fish Value (%) Fish Value (cumulative %)
LP012 Pristipomoides multidens 78365.4 0.50 2.8e+09 0.45 0.45
LL021 Lutjanus malabaricus 30791.5 0.20 1.6e+09 0.25 0.70
LP014 Pristipomoides typus 6818.7 0.04 2.7e+08 0.04 0.74
SE002 Epinephelus areolatus 6512.2 0.04 1.4e+08 0.02 0.84
LL019 Lutjanus johnii 7.1 0.00 2.0e+05 0.00 1.00

The main risk however is that all the medium boat tracked (based on which we compute % of weight landed) are either in Probolinggo or Brondong, while the great majority of medium boats actually departs from Pati. This is a problem because by just using depth contours, it looks like most multidens ought to be north-east of Java.

Also, we currently have no survey of those boats anywhere. I am unsure how long their trips are, how much money they make and so on.

Big

There are 53 big boats, half in Probolinggo, half in Pati.

Species Weight Caught (kg) Weight Caught (%) Fish Value (IDR) Fish Value (%) Fish Value (cumulative %)
LP012 Pristipomoides multidens 32187.3 0.55 1.2e+09 0.50 0.50
LL021 Lutjanus malabaricus 9237.4 0.16 4.9e+08 0.21 0.71
LP014 Pristipomoides typus 2782.3 0.05 1.1e+08 0.05 0.76
SE002 Epinephelus areolatus 1394.0 0.02 3.2e+07 0.01 0.87
LL019 Lutjanus johnii 4.1 0.00 1.3e+05 0.00 1.00

They catch predominantly multidens, but again this is only true for boats in Probolinggo.

Again, we don’t have them in surveys. From Josep’s table we know their trip length is between 30 to 60 days long. They might travel 10 days to get there.
There is one Rani’s interview in the “supply chain deliverable” document about a large (>30GT) captain and it mentions 2-4 trips a year, 60 days long.

  • Distances too high
    • Makes sense, operational costs are not included
  • Profits too low
    • Targets are revenues, not profits
